    <fr:title text="Forester 4.0 › forest configuration via TOML"><fr:link href="foreign-forester-jms-00RF.xml" title="Forester 4.0" addr="//forester/jms-00RF" type="local">Forester 4.0</fr:link> › forest configuration via TOML</fr:title>
  </fr:frontmatter>
  <fr:mainmatter>
    <fr:p>Previously, the locations of trees as well as assets and theme directories were configured by means of command line arguments. As this has become a bit unwieldy, especially as many users have multiple projections of their forest, we have consolidated these options under a simple <fr:link href="https://toml.io/en/" type="external">TOML</fr:link> configuration file whose location is the first argument to most <fr:code>forester</fr:code> commands. Here is an example configuration file:</fr:p>
    <fr:pre><![CDATA[# forest.toml
[forest]
trees = ["trees"]
assets = ["assets"]
theme = "theme"
root = "jms-0001"
base_url = "https://www.jonmsterling.com"]]></fr:pre>
    <fr:p>It is common to have multiple configurations. For example, if you have “public” trees located in a specific directory, you can have an additional configuration:</fr:p>
    <fr:pre><![CDATA[# public.toml
[forest]
trees = ["trees/public"]
assets = ["assets"]
theme = "theme"
root = "jms-0001"
base_url = "https://www.jonmsterling.com"]]></fr:pre>
    <fr:p>Both the <fr:code>assets</fr:code> and <fr:code>theme</fr:code> keys are displayed above with their default values, so they could be omitted. There is an additional <fr:code>stylesheet</fr:code> key that can be used to set the name of the XSL stylesheet used (the default is <fr:code>forest.xsl</fr:code>).</fr:p>
    <fr:p>To build the forest, simply run: <fr:code>forester build forest.toml</fr:code>; other options can be used (see <fr:code>forester build --help</fr:code>), such as <fr:code>forester build forest.toml --dev</fr:code>.</fr:p>
  </fr:mainmatter>
